body:
I am not sure what the exact problem is here. I think it might be the implicit dropping of the transaction.
I am using sqlx = "0.4.0-beta.1" with the postgres feature. Here is the code to reproduce the problem:

```
use anyhow::Context;
use sqlx::Acquire;

#[async_std::main]
async fn main() -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    // Setup
    dotenv::dotenv().ok();
    let uri = std::env::var("DATABASE_URL")
        .with_context(|| "Environment variable not found".to_string())?;
    let pool = sqlx::PgPool::connect(&uri)
        .await
        .context("Failed to connect to database")?;
    let mut conn = pool.acquire().await?;

    // Clean up
    sqlx::query!("DELETE FROM area").execute(&mut conn).await?;

    // First iteration works, second crashes
    for _ in 0..2 {
        transaction(&mut conn).await?;

        let count = sqlx::query!("SELECT COUNT(*) FROM area")
            .fetch_one(&mut conn)
            .await
            // "RowNotFound" in second iteration
            .unwrap()
            .count
            .unwrap_or(0);

        dbg!(count);
    }

    Ok(())
}

async fn transaction(conn: &mut sqlx::PgConnection) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    let mut transaction = conn.begin().await?;

    let _area = sqlx::query!("INSERT INTO area (name) VALUES ('foo') RETURNING *")
        .fetch_one(&mut transaction)
        .await?;

    // Implicit rollback
    // transaction.rollback().await?;

    Ok(())
}
```

Error message:

```
thread 'main' panicked at 'called `Result::unwrap()` on an `Err` value: RowNotFound', 
src\main.rs:22:21
note: run with `RUST_BACKTRACE=1` environment variable to display a backtrace
error: process didn't exit successfully: `target\debug\sqlx-test.exe` (exit code: 101)
```

The first iteration of the for loop always works, the second crashes.
Explicitly calling `transaction.rollback().await?;` seems to fix the problem, which is not hard in this example but not so easy in more complex code.

If there is nothing wrong on my side and it helps, I can publish the repository of this code to reproduce it easier.

Edit: Removing the `RETURNING *` in the `transaction()` function and just use `execute` instead of `fetch_one` fixes the crash, too.
Edit2: It seems to be important if the last query before the implicit rollback is a "returning" query or not. "returning" = crash
